--- Feb 3 Email Response ---

Hi Soren,

Sorry we missed you at the show, it was pretty busy there.

The round style manhole aeration will fit the Meridian bins.  From what I can tell it should fit the Frontier and Norstar bins as well.  As long as the opening is 21 or less across and 25 or less tall this should fit those manholes.  I just dont have experience with those two makes of bins.

I see no problems with it on a 1630 and 1620 bin.  I believe the very first bin we tried this on was either a 1615 or a 1617.

We have not had any problems with the strength of the bin or the Manhole Aeration tube.  When the bin empties, the flow is coming through the center of the bin and we have kept the tube short enough that it does not protrude into the center of the bin.  This was to reduce the forces that are put on the tube when the bin is emptied.

The show pricing was to the end of the show.  Since you werent able to speak with us at the show, we could likely still offer a discount though.

If you have any further questions, please reach out to me.

Regards,

Jason Griffith

Wavcor International Inc.

My name is Trent Larson, owner of Lars Bros Ag LLC, an independent ag dealership serving North Dakota, South Dakota, eastern Montana, and western Minnesota.

Im currently expanding our grain storage & handling division and came across your Airblast Fan and the rest of the Wavcor product line. After reviewing your systems fans, ducting, manhole aeration, and DRYit radial flow I believe this could be a strong fit for what our growers are asking for.

 

We work directly with farms across the Upper Midwest, and our customer base is growing fast. Between Rock Dams, Sunnybrook Concaves, Bourgault/Niaux blades, NorBin hopper aeration, grain handling accessories, and our enzyme/foliar program, were building out a complete lineup of high-performance tools for grain management. Wavcor looks like the next logical step in that expansion.

 

Before I move forward, Id like to learn what it takes to offer Wavcor products as a dealer/distributor:

 

A few quick questions:

Do you currently work with independent dealers in the U.S. Upper Midwest?

What does your dealer program require (pricing, margins, minimums, territories)?

Do you ship direct into the U.S., or do orders route through a Canadian distributor?

Any compatibility notes for common bin brands in ND/SD (Westeel, Chief, GSI, Sioux)?

Do you offer dealer literature or technical sheets for your Airblast and aeration systems?

 

We expect to more than double our customer count going into 2026, and there is clear demand for a propane/natural-gas powered aeration and drying solution especially at remote bin sites with limited electrical service.

 

If youre open to a conversation, Id like to schedule a call and see how we can work together.

 

Thank you,
